2022-01-20 00:31:21	cheapie	Compression is a separate standard (that most modems do support).
2022-01-20 00:32:24	cheapie	V.34+/V.34bis (in use here) does 33.6k uncompressed, a bit more compressed, while V.90 and V.92 do 56k uncompressed.
2022-01-20 00:32:43	cheapie	(53k-ish in the US)
2022-01-20 00:33:54	<--	Hashida (~Itaru@185.65.135.251) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2022-01-20 00:34:00	rastan	ah didnt think the phone lines could do 56k uncompressed on a modem
2022-01-20 00:34:24	cheapie	They can, barely, in the right circumstances, with the right modem type at the other end.
2022-01-20 00:35:29	<--	kts (~kts@103.73.237.13) has quit (Quit: Konversation terminated!)
2022-01-20 00:35:41	rastan	been so long since i used a modem. used to keep a 24/7 dedicated connection over 28.8 for a domain i had. was pretty stupid tho because any time it disconnected and someone sent an email, it was just lost
2022-01-20 00:35:48	cheapie	Specifically, the answering (but not calling) modem needs to be connected to the digital sort of backbone part of the telephone network, and not a normal phone line. If it's on a normal phone line you get 33.6k at most.
2022-01-20 00:36:10	<--	ncuxo (~ident@ip-109-43-114-68.web.vodafone.de) has quit (Quit: Konversation terminated!)
2022-01-20 00:36:42	cheapie	(something about the 56k signals surviving the DACs but not the ADCs)
2022-01-20 00:36:44	rastan	ahh
2022-01-20 00:37:17	cheapie	I'm using a line simulator, with a normal analog modem connected to the other port - so 33.6 max here.
